<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Padres-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Padres bump Astros in 10 innings
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Another game, another loss.
</P>
<P>
   The season is not yet a month old and the Astros have
experienced almost every imaginable way to lose.
</P>
<P>
   There have been blowouts and close calls, starting pitching
nightmares and bullpen breakdowns. And don't forget a near
no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   They found another way Saturday afternoon _ extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   A botched pickoff attempt, a wild pitch and one misplaced
fastball were just a few of the factors that sent the Astros to
their fifth loss in six games, an 8-6 defeat to the San Diego
Padres in 10 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're getting tougher and tougher to lose as the days go on,
particularly at home,'' said manager Larry Dierker, whose team is
2-6 at Enron Field. ``We were just sloppy. The way things are going
now we can't afford to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros fell behind early, briefly took the lead and later
forced extra innings with a two-run rally in the sixth. Padres
catcher Carlos Hernandez, activated from the disabled list earlier
in the day, hit a two-run double off lefthander Yorkis Perez with
two out in the 10th inning to provide the winning runs.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of problems began long before.
</P>
<P>
   On the first pitch of the game, Al Martin doubled to left field.
He later scored. In the second inning, Astros starter Chris Holt,
who remained winless in four starts, threw away a ball on a pickoff
attempt, which eventually led to a run.
</P>
<P>
   A wild pitch by Holt in the third allowed Tony Gwynn to advance
from second to third; he scored a couple of pitches later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play better,'' said first baseman Jeff Bagwell, who
homered for the sixth time in nine games. ``We have to pitch
better. We have to hit better. We have to play better defense. We
just have to be a better ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt allowed six runs and 10 hits in six innings but avoided his
fourth loss when Roger Cedeno tied the score at 6 with a two-out,
two-run single off Donne Wall in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Holt has allowed 26 earned runs, the most in the National
League. Opponents are hitting .409 against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not overly disappointed with my performance,'' Holt said.
``The ball I threw away at first and the wild pitch cost me. Those
are big parts of the game. You have to be able to make those plays.
It wasn't a bad game, but I wish we could have been on the winning
end of it. ``We're in a funk right now, but we're not going to stay
in this forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's two-run homer off Matt Clement in the fifth cleared
the railroad tracks above the left-field seats and landed on
Crawford Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Caminiti hit his second homer of the season, a two-out,
two-run shot into the bullpen in right-center in the first inning,
and Craig Biggio extended his hitting streak to 13 games, one shy
of his career high. Cedeno was 2-for-3 with two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   That was the extent of the offense (six hits Saturday), whose
members' pictures are now appearing on milk cartons in the Houston
area. San Diego pitchers combined for 14 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had runners in scoring position in the third inning
but came up empty when Richard Hidalgo struck out to end the
inning. With runners at first and second and one out in the
seventh, Martin's diving catch robbed Mitch Meluskey and prevented
the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're playing like we are right now you usually aren't
getting any breaks,'' Biggio said.
</P>
<P>
   The longest bomb of the day was reserved for Padres first
baseman Ryan Klesko, who became the first player to clear the wall
in straightaway center field with a shot estimated at 440 feet.
</P>
<P>
   His sixth-inning home run gave the Padres a 6-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four-forty? I think it went a lot farther than that,'' San
Diego manager Bruce Bochy said. ``That ball would have gone out
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
