<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REALIGNMENT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Baseball on its way to getting radical with realignment
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ALAN TRUEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Three years ago, David Glass, CEO of the Kansas City Royals, issued
a blueprint for restructuring Major League Baseball. In the
interests of grouping everyone geographically, he would move nine
teams across league boundaries that had stood firm for almost a
century.
</P>
<P>
   The national media dubbed it ``radical realignment'' and
literally wrote it off as something that would never be imposed on
tradition-bound baseball. The Mets, Astros and Reds in the American
League? The White Sox and Athletics in the National?
</P>
<P>
   But as far-fetched as that proposal seemed, it drew support from
Bud Selig, the commissioner who has a knack for getting his way and
realigning the sport every three years or 50,000 miles, whichever
comes sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Selig reaches his goals slowly, one step at a time, never
letting the owners vote on anything until he's sure they're ready
to agree. After baseball's owners met last week in Houston, Selig
has more lobbying to do between now and June before he seeks
enactment of what he terms ``modest realignment'' for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, calling this realignment ``modest'' is like saying
Shiloh was a skirmish. In the reshuffling Selig proposed, the wild
card will be withdrawn from the National League, which will
introduce a new division, the Southeast, which, geography
notwithstanding, somehow will include Cincinnati, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The composition of all six currently existing divisions will
change, and two teams (Arizona, Tampa Bay) will switch leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But that's far from enough to satisfy Selig.
</P>
<P>
   When his master plan is completed, baseball will be reorganized
regionally, with a centralized format like that of the National
Basketball Association and National Hockey League. If the National
and American leagues continue to exist, they will bear little
resemblance to their appearance today.
</P>
<P>
   Selig took a major step toward centralization by abolishing the
National and American League offices. Last year, he dismissed NL
president Leonard Coleman and AL president Gene Budig.
Surprisingly, that shakeup did not elicit much outcry from media,
fans or baseball owners and executives.
</P>
<P>
   Tal Smith, president of the Astros, said, ``I don't think it's
had any real effect on anything. The main things the league
presidents dealt with were supervising the umpires and performing
some disciplinary functions.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that with interleague play, ``It doesn't make sense
to have a perception that there's a difference in umpiring between
the two leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course, the more the two leagues become the same, the
less radical it seems to abolish them altogether. Even so, Smith
and Astros owner Drayton McLane want to see the leagues holding
onto some vestiges of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you abolish the league delineations,'' Smith said, ``I
think that initially would bother a lot of fans. More than other
sports, baseball has depended on its history, its records and
traditions as part of its appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   But is that changing?
</P>
<P>
   Royals president Mike Hermann believes the leagues no longer
have any real meaning and that fans are becoming increasingly
ambivalent about league identification.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our fans identify us that much as an American
League team,'' he said. ``There's not as much sensitivity to league
affiliation as there was in the 1950s and '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has found that among younger fans, ``there may not be as
much sensitivity about traditional league alignments as you get
from people who have been in the game a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermann pointed out that in the past decade, expansions,
realignments and the arrival of interleague play blurred
distinctions between the leagues, as did the recent turn to
standardized umpiring.
</P>
<P>
   And with widespread free agency, which began in the 1970s,
players continually bolt from team to team and league to league.
Many fans who preferred the AL because Ken Griffey Jr. was in it
may change allegiance with Griffey now playing for Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   However, one significant distinction that remains is the
designated hitter for the AL. If the two leagues become one, the DH
would be an all-or-nothing proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to work something out with the players' union,''
Hermann said. ``If the DH went away, it wouldn't be the worst thing
to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is not the position of the Players Association, which
has the right to veto all of the Selig/Glass remodeling plans. The
union has refused to drop the DH, even when Major League Baseball
has offered to add a 26th roster position, thus creating a net gain
of union members.
</P>
<P>
   As the union sees it _ and also the owners, for that matter _
the DH is a high-salaried position that boosts the salaries of
other players.
</P>
<P>
   So why, with all the obstacles and objections to radical
realignment, does Selig push it, albeit gently?
</P>
<P>
   Foremost, he wants to promote rivalries, the lifeblood of any
team sport. He speaks nostalgically of baseball's most glorious
era, the 1940s and '50s, when the Brooklyn Dodgers and neighboring
New York Giants battled head-to-head throughout the National League
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   And there are other reasons for radical realignment besides
rivalry-making. Nobody faults Selig for trying to change a system
that has teams playing half their games during hours that bring
reduced television ratings and out-of-prime-time advertising rates.
</P>
<P>
   Selig and Glass hope they can raise the competitiveness of
small-market clubs with realignment along regional lines, combined
with an ``unbalanced'' schedule offering teams more games against
their nearby rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees and Los Angeles Dodgers can attract
near-capacity crowds regardless of the opponent, but that cannot be
said of small-market teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never have the competitive balance we once had,'' Glass
said. ``But I think all the owners are ready to take steps to
narrow the gap, so small-market teams at least have a shot at
postseason play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royals draw well when hosting Midwestern teams. ``A lot of
people who live in our town come from Chicago and St. Louis,''
Hermann said. ``They don't come from Seattle and Anaheim. West
Coast people tend to stay on the West Coast and Midwest people in
the Midwest when they change jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Chicago and St. Louis come into our town, they draw much
better than Anaheim and Seattle. And when we go out there, we don't
draw well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Glass plan of 1997 had the National League composed of
mostly western cities, with the American League composed of eastern
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Under this format, Hermann said, ``fans would see the teams they
want to see, and games won't be starting at 11 o'clock. You'd have
more interleague games, but you'd have a core of geographic games
like we have in other sports.''
</P>
<P>
   But others dispute the allure of regional matchups.
</P>
<P>
   When Glass tried to group all the Pacific teams together, he met
opposition in San Francisco and Los Angeles. Owners were unwilling
to exchange games with the storied Yankees and Boston Red Sox for
more dates with far-less-glamorous teams down the block _ Oakland
or San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   George Burks, a Houston attorney who spent many of his boyhood
hours in Brooklyn's Ebbets Field, questions whether Selig is on the
right track with radical realignment: ``You're talking about
overturning a lot of tradition, to try to get that kind of great
rivalry that can't happen again anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Giants came into Brooklyn, you'd have fisticuffs if
you were in the wrong section of the stands. Everybody lived
baseball. In the '50s you could go to ballgames or the movies or
watch black-and-white television on a miniscule screen. Now the
entertainment dollar is so much more diffused.''
</P>
<P>
   And with travel becoming ever faster and cable and satellite
television channels multiplying, Americans are not as regionalist
as they once were. While leagues may be losing significance, so is
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Midwesterners may tend to stay in the Midwest, as Hermann
suggests, but migration to the West and Sun Belt during the past
two decades suggests a weakening of geographical ties.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, there seems little demand for radical realignment or
geographic purity. Although this city is hardly a bedrock of
baseball tradition, it does maintain National League roots back to
the Houston Buffs, once a farm club of the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, fans here protested vigorously when McLane
indicated willingness in 1997 to change leagues.
</P>
<P>
   McLane desperately wanted the Astros in regular-season games
with the Texas Rangers, and he's likely to see his wish fulfilled
next season. But his hopes for an intrastate rivalry depend on both
teams being contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the best rivalries in sports have nothing to do with
geography,'' Smith observed. ``Look at the Oilers and Pittsburgh
Steelers, or the (Los Angeles) Lakers and (Chicago) Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``And even though Philadelphia is geographically close to the
New York Mets, I wouldn't call that a great rivalry. I think
rivalries are created by who your competition is.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith isn't sure baseball helps itself with its frequent
makeovers. ``Personally, I'd like to see the divisions stay the
same for a while and let the rivalries develop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you need is an unbalanced schedule so teams are playing a
lot of games against their division rivals in September. But to get
that, you need divisions with an even number of teams.''
</P>
<P>
   He likes the proposed wild-cardless National League realignment
for 2001, which has four divisions of four teams each. But the AL
does not set up so neatly, with its 14 teams to be dispersed in two
divisions of four and one of six.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, you'd like to add two teams to get 32,'' Smith said.
``But with some troubled franchises now, expansion is not on the
horizon. I think there's more chance of contraction than
expansion.''
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Twins are practically on life support, as were the
Montreal Expos before a recent change of ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Smith does not consider Minnesota and Montreal historical
anomalies. ``We've had franchises before that almost failed _ such
as San Diego and San Francisco _ and somebody always stepped up,''
he said. ``But I'm not sure that will keep happening.''
</P>
<P>
   With teams coming and perhaps going, it may be impossible to
develop the structural stability to promote the rivalries everyone
wants. But count on Selig to keep trying.
</P>
<P>
   The 2001 realignment will be the third for baseball in eight
years. By advancing his agenda gradually, Selig can make radical
realignment seem not radical at all. And sooner than you expect, it
may be done.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
