<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Spurs set game back a few years
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Tim Duncan has a bad left knee. But it was the
rest of the Spurs who appeared lame.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Elliott has a transplanted kidney. But what the remaining
Spurs needed Saturday was a better shooting eye and a functioning
brain.
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back? Or flat-on-their-backs?
</P>
<P>
   Defending champs? Or defending chumps?
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs opened the NBA 2000 new millennium playoffs with an
effort straight out of the Dark Ages. All that was missing was
garbage in the streets and the bubonic plague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can do better,'' David Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what the marketing geniuses at the baseball game said
the day after Roseanne sang the national anthem. This was just as
off-key.
</P>
<P>
   The official conclusion came when Mario Elie drifted a lazy pass
out toward the middle of the floor to Samaki Walker with 0.7
seconds left to play and it was intercepted by Rodney Rogers to
wrap up Phoenix's 72-70 win. But the end could have come any time
earlier in the afternoon when the Spurs looked ready or able to
compete.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day when the definition of ugly was stretched to new
limits. Missed layups. Errant free throws. Mindless passes. And
that was by the winners.
</P>
<P>
   Don't even bother to look at the final score and leap to any
conclusions about great defense. This equaled the lowest combined
score by two teams in a playoff game since the inception of the
shot clock only because of offensive ineptitude.
</P>
<P>
   How did they reach playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   Artistically, it was the equivalent of two teams tossing
elephant dung onto a canvas and trying to pass it off as a
masterpiece. It was hard to believe each team won 53 regular-season
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns struggled and the Spurs labored. Phoenix's Cliff
Robinson misfired at 6-for-18 shooting. The Spurs' David Robinson
was lucky he didn't hurt himself at 3-for-12.
</P>
<P>
   ``David was slowed in the first half by other factors,'' said
Spurs coach Gregg Popovich.
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about the officiating, which saddled The Admiral
with two personal fouls in the first quarter and a third with 5:09
left in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But long before that, Robinson appeared to have taken himself
out of the game, allowing the less-than-bullish Luc Longley to push
him around at one end of the floor and settling far too often for
jump shots at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   On the rare occasion when Robinson demanded the ball in the
paint, turned and powered to the hoop, he scored or drew a foul.
But he did it infrequently.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs shot a horrid 27-of-73 (37 percent) from the field by
relying on the likes of Terry Porter (2-for-7), Mario Elie
(0-for-5) and Malik Rose (3-for-8) to take too many of them.
</P>
<P>
   But they always had a chance because the Suns were miserable on
offense, connecting at 36.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you put Elie together with the Suns' Randy Livingston
(1-for-6), the ex-Rockets factor had a large hand in the game
plummeting to new depths.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game when Popovich did not appear to distinguish
himself with a pair of curious personnel decisions in the fourth
quarter. First, he took Walker, his best rebounder on the day with
16, out of the game with just under nine minutes to play, and
Popovich also went the first 7{ minutes of the fourth quarter with
Antonio Daniels at point guard instead of quarterback Avery
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``That team was playing well,'' Popovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Everything, of course, being relative.
</P>
<P>
   Even coach had bad day
</P>
<P>
   With David Robinson frustrated by his foul situation and Elliott
retreating into a fourth-quarter shell in terms of taking shots,
the Spurs went through a crucial stretch where they left the
offense in the hands of Porter and Daniels. For nearly five minutes
of the final period, Porter and Daniels combined to miss five of
six shots and committed two turnovers; no other Spur got a look at
the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the last eight seconds, Elliott passed up an open trey
to drive, only to put up an airball.
</P>
<P>
   It was reminiscent of the line by the old basketball coach when
asked about his team's execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in favor of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This season has not been without its challenges,'' David
Robinson said. ``This is just another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the talk will turn to Duncan and whether he can return for
Tuesday's Game 2. Just the thought shows the Spurs' dire straits.
</P>
<P>
   In the history of the best-of-five first round, the winner of
Game 1 has gone on to take the series 83 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a math major,'' Robinson said. ``And that 17 percent is
a lot bigger than you think.''
</P>
<P>
   The defending champs or defending chumps are already playing the
numbers game.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
