u s BC-BKN-SPURS-HNS &LR;      04-23 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Suns manage ragged victory over Spurs
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN ANTONIO _ With the defending champions in the house, Saturday's
game between the San Antonio Spurs and the Phoenix Suns was
supposed to be one of the day's marquee matchups.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it looked like the off-Broadway production of the 2000
NBA playoffs, with stand-ins doing much of the work for the lead
characters. No Tim Duncan, no Jason Kidd and no Tom Gugliotta.
</P>
<P>
   And not much of a game, as it turned out, because most of the
stand-ins took that meaning literally, mostly inert on offense and
defense. But because somebody had to win, the Suns managed to steal
the first game of the NBA Western Conference opener 72-70 before
21,916 at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we play San Antonio it's been like this,'' said
Phoenix coach Scott Skiles of the less-than-artistic game. ``It's
always low-scoring and everybody seems to shoot in the 40s
(percentage-wise). It's very ugly, but very exciting basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Exciting? Well, the game did come down to the last play, which
must constitute excitement of some kind.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, San Antonio had one last try at a tie (or a win), down
by two points with seven-tenths of a second left and the ball out
of bounds at midcourt. But, in keeping with the shoddy nature of
the game, Mario Elie's pass was picked off by Rodney Rogers,
leaving the Spurs on the short end of the game and the series,
which continues here Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we would have lost that game in the last second, I would
have cried,'' said the Suns' Corie Blount. ``I have never cried
about basketball in my life, but if we would have lost this one
tonight, that would have been the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Blount didn't have to, because the Spurs were doing plenty of
crying for both teams. The cried about the officiating, they cried
about the physical nature of the Suns' inside players and they
cried about missing Duncan, who was on the sidelines with torn
cartilage in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   But the Suns aren't the healthiest team, either. Without Kidd
and Gugliotta, both starters, they've had to scramble, too, even
luring longtime Sun Kevin Johnson out of retirement. Penny Hardaway
(17 points) and Cliff Robinson (17 points) did their jobs, but it
was Johnson (six assists in 25 minutes) and Blount (five points,
six rebounds) who contributed as the Suns made the plays down the
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case with the Spurs, who never seemed to find
any kind of rhythm (18 turnovers) or shooting eye (game tied
playoff record for fewest points).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our offense, the execution just wasn't there,'' Elie said.
``This was a very frustrating loss.''
</P>
<P>
   All the more frustrating because the Spurs could have won. With
eight seconds remaining, Sean Elliott found himself with the ball
in his hands and a chance to reprise his role as hero from last
season. Instead, Elliott saw his last jumper _ a leaning 11-footer
_ fall a foot short, giving the Suns the ball with a second left.
</P>
<P>
   But Elliott, who split the Suns' Cliff Robinson and Kevin
Johnson on the play, appeared to be smacked on the head by
Robinson, causing his shot to fall short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I wouldn't say he smacked me,'' said Elliott, who
finished with 15 points on 6-of-14 shooting. ``Let's say he grazed
my head. But I just missed the shot. I give credit to Cliff
Robinson. He made me change the shot a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the Spurs' 37 percent shooting, the Suns, who are
less-than-noteworthy on defense, made them change a lot of shots.
And nowhere was that more evident than inside.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs did not have Duncan, sidelined with torn cartilage in
his left knee. But the Spurs knew beforehand they would be minus
one of their twin towers.
</P>
<P>
   What they didn't realize was they would be without both for much
of the game. Or so it seemed, as David Robinson struggled through
one of the worst playoff games of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, relying mostly on outside jumpers, made just three of
12 shots while playing against the likes of Blount, Luc Longley and
Oliver Miller, none of whom will be confused with Hakeem Olajuwon
defensively.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether Robinson, who finished with 11 points and 11
rebounds, was bothered by soreness in his right knee, San Antonio
coach Gregg Popovich said: ``No, David's fine. He was slowed
tonight by other factors.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to elaborate, Popovich forced a smile and said:
``You'll just have to read my mind on that one. And that shouldn't
be too tough. I'm a pretty simple guy.''
</P>
<P>
   And Robinson had a simple explanation _ officiating. Robinson
was called for three fouls in his 10 first-half minutes, and he
didn't like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only playing eight or 10 minutes in that first half is kind of
tough,'' Robinson said. ``You go back in the second half and it's
hard _ you want to get things rolling pretty quick. But I'm going
to have to make some adjustments in the next game and play a little
better.''
</P>
<P>
   He can watch tapes of Samaki Walker, who tore up the Suns with
13 points, 16 rebounds and three blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   But this wasn't a game for the stars, was it?
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
