<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Little nostalgia for Enron Field
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We used to speak fondly of the Astros' Dome-field advantage,
although it never really was much of one, translating into only two
division titles over 32 mostly mediocre seasons _ and far more
empty seats than occupied ones.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, it wasn't until the decision came down to replace the
Astrodome that the home team went from being peasants to pheasants
under glass. The Astros were 3-for-3 in Central Division titles
after the referendum to build Enron Field passed.
</P>
<P>
   So please excuse them if they're feeling pangs of nostalgia for
their dark and gloomy erstwhile house of pain. Because once again
Saturday, there would be nothing friendly about the cozy confines
of Home-ron Field. Fortunately, the multitude of fans, crammed into
every nook and cranny of the old-fashioned new park, appear to be
having so much darned fun visiting the Astros' new digs that
they've hardly noticed the hole their heroes are digging for
themselves on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Another SRO crowd, another sorrowful performance against a
second-tier ballclub. If the Astros can't beat the Phillies and the
Padres here, what chance do they have?
</P>
<P>
   That's not a trick question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to play better baseball,'' said Jeff Bagwell,
although he is personally blameless with six home runs and 16 RBIs
on the season. ``We need a better team effort.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears the Astros don't have to win to sell tickets for the
near term, but the few purists among the throngs pouring downtown
are grumbling, as they should be. It's not a pitcher-perfect
setting, to be sure, but the inviting fences haven't stopped San
Diego from holding the Astros to just a pair of runs Friday night,
then to six paltry hits Saturday in an 8-6 extra-inning victory.
</P>
<P>
   Six runs used to mean something down on Kirby Drive. On Crawford
Street, six runs will only get you beat. Fact: After eight games,
six of them Astros losses, the bad guys are averaging 6.25 per. If
the so-called Gas House is going to be a hitter's park, which seems
a foregone conclusion with the roof open, then the Astros had best
stop taking the gas at the plate and get with the program
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Their National League-worst .228 batting average is more of a
drag than their NL-worse 5.81 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``These days, with these new parks,'' Bagwell said, ``you've got
to score runs to give yourself a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   And surely the Astros will. As Baggy was quick to point out,
cleanup hitter Ken Caminiti is no more than ``75 to 80 percent''
with his strained hamstring and Moises Alou, limping with a calf
injury, hadn't played in five games before he struck out pinch
hitting to end Saturday's sad affair. Once they start
sweet-stroking, and assuming center fielder Roger Cedeno finally
has found his swing, the Astros should glean as much pleasure from
the funky ball yard as their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, the amazin' young Met turned dismayin' Astro, jacked his
average up 26 points on the afternoon _ to .196 _ with a single, a
double and two walks in five plate appearances. The aforementioned
single banged off the right-field fence, too, driving in the two
tying runs in the sixth inning and increasing his RBI count to five
for the season.
</P>
<P>
   He also would steal four bases, tying the club's record and
equaling his personally most larcenous day in New York, where he
pilfered a gaudy 66 in 1999. For one 3{-hour interlude at least,
Mike Hampton wouldn't be missed, especially the control-challenged
Mike Hampton the Mets have seen.
</P>
<P>
   It was beginning to be feared Cedeno didn't fit in as a new-age
Astro, that he arrived in Houston a year too late. But perhaps he
gave us a reason to keep our minds open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to run,'' manager Larry Dierker said, ``and Roger can
run.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming he gets on base.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the total Enron experience, Astros pitchers will prove
a much harder sell, of course. But they would be wise to stop
fighting the problem. Hey, fellas, you're stuck. The boss, Drayton
McLane Jr., signed a 30-year lease, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chris Holt was the latest victim, giving up six more
earned runs and 10 hits over six innings, he isn't necessarily
suffering from an edifice complex. Remember, he gave up 10 runs and
12 hits in three innings in San Diego. The Padres are batting .512
against Holt, as in jolt. And he had problems throwing accurately
to everybody, not just catcher Tony Eusebio, as an errant toss on
an attempted pickoff at first also set up a San Diego run.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he was the hard-luck kid. This year he has simply
turned into his own worst enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Chris isn't pitching with a lot of confidence right
now,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are many of his teammates bubbling over with same.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell was asked what needs to happen for the Astros to get
things pointed in the right direction before the Cardinals start to
vanish from their radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see Ellie (Scott Elarton) pitch a shutout
(today),'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance. Considering there have been 29 home runs in the
park's first eight games, Elarton probably wishes he was making his
2000 debut in a safer place. Say Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get back to where we're excited about coming home
to play,'' Dierker said. ``Like other teams.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
