<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTH HURTS IN NHL, SO YOU LIE A LOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock was telling blatant lies late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Except ...
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. Maybe Hitchcock's words and his intention were as
pure as the driven slush, which passes these days for Reunion ice.
</P>
<P>
   Except ...
</P>
<P>
   In the wacky world of the NHL playoffs, there is no such thing
as a blatant lie, even if you repeatedly tell a whopper. No coach
or general manager in his right mind would actually speak the truth
about his team's injuries.
</P>
<P>
   So there was a relieved Hitchcock, mere minutes after his Dallas
Stars had ousted Edmonton in the first postseason series, standing
on the media room podium talking about how two very valuable team
components, Sergei Zubov and Jere Lehtinen,
might-be-could-be-definitely-will-be ready to play in Round Two.
Except ...
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the same things about Zubov and Lehtinen before
and during the Edmonton series. Neither, of course, came close to
putting one blade on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   But Hitchcock rushed Friday night to get the word out fast to
both Colorado and San Jose. One of these clubs will show up at
Reunion this week for Game 1 of the Western Conference semifinals.
The Stars' coach wanted those opponents to have an immediate
mind-set, not to mention an extensive scouting report, which must
account for the return of two big horses to the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Is Hitchcock lying? Absolutely not, at least under the
long-standing NHL definition. This stuff is called important
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also called survival,'' Stars broadcaster Daryl Reaugh,
the former NHL goalie, noted. ``On injuries, you always want the
other side to wonder, and you do so by spewing as much
misinformation as you can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the playoffs arrive, all injured players will be listed
as day-to-day. A guy can have an arm severed, but the club will
tell you the arm has been frozen and will be reattached. So he's
still day-to-day.''
</P>
<P>
   With Zubov and Lehtinen, however, it goes far beyond this
accepted gamesmanship. Logic says the Stars will not repeat as
Stanley Cup champs without at least Zubov being back to 100 percent
and being his usual valuable self in all areas. And when it comes
to valuable, the long-standing theory says Lehtinen is the team
MVP. The Stars made do during the regular season and in the first
round without him, but the grueling grind of the playoffs has only
just begun. No Lehtinen might well mean no Cup.
</P>
<P>
   For those guessing along, the popular notion says Zubov's knee
has improved and he will play in the next round, but Lehtinen's
ankle remains a mess and he's out for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't believe that, then go ask Hitchcock or Bob
Gainey. Just be sure to take along Judge Judy and a Bible. Sworn
testimony will be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere else in professional sports, certainly not among the Big
Four, is such deceit about injuries either allowed or practiced.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL, it's flat outlawed. The hiding of injuries can cost
a team tens of thousands of dollars in fines. The league office has
to be strict because so much money is wagered, legally and
illegally, on NFL games. Any perception of ``inside information''
being available on injuries would lead to a credibility disaster or
a scandal. Yet, even with the league being diligent and strict in
this area, there's always a question about some wiseguys still
having that inside info on injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball and in the NBA, roster numbers are frozen, as
opposed to the ``healthy'' or ``injured'' pregame scratches in the
NHL. If a player is injured, it benefits a team in baseball or the
NBA to place him on the disabled list and bring in a healthy body.
In most cases, the hiding of injuries would be detrimental in those
sports.
</P>
<P>
   But the physical demands of hockey, combined with the toughness
of hockey players, also puts injuries in a different category from
all sports except maybe football.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL is the closest, but I don't know if football players
go to the extremes that hockey players do when it comes to injuries
this time of year,'' Reaugh said. ``The code is that you do not
hurt in the playoffs. You may be injured, but you do not hurt. No
matter what's ailing, or what body part may be about to fall off,
don't explain, don't complain. Just press on.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaugh's rule of thumb for the playoffs is this:
</P>
<P>
   ``The more pain your team has, that usually equates to more
wins. I don't know if anyone has ever done a survey, but I'd say
there are more off-season surgeries by the Stanley Cup champion
than any other team. Sure, that club played more games, but what I
think it means is the champion had more players able to play
through the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes, however, to finding out the truth about those
injuries, don't expect any George Washingtons to step forward. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
