<HEADLINE>
TOP SPRINTER JOHNSON STARTS FAST, CUTS BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Johnson's month in Africa told him all he needed to know
about his readiness for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   In three spectacular performances at a series of meets in South
Africa, the world's most dominant sprinter put up
gold-medal-caliber times in his specialties, the 200 and 400
meters, and threw in a world record at the rarely-run distance of
300 meters. As a result, Johnson pulled out ofthe Michael Johnson
Open on Saturday in Waco, the meet at which he usually makes his
season debut in America, and has reduced his competitive schedule
for the season to a bare minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will run a 4x400 relay at next weekend's Penn Relays in
Philadelphia because of commitments to his major sponsor, Nike. But
he is likely to run just one more race between then and the Olympic
trials in July, said his coach, Clyde Hart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to get back into training and reload,'' Hart said.
``Remember, what he did (in South Africa) was before he really got
into his training. He hadn't done any speed work. He went over
there to test himself, and I think he showed everyone where he
is.''
</P>
<P>
   That's at the top of the world, as usual. His time of 19.71
seconds in the 200 ranks No. 1 in the world, and his 43.9 in the
400 would if it hadn't been hand-timed due to a failure in the
automatic timing system. Obviously in top form, Johnson will now
trade competition for more training for the Games this September in
Sydney, Australia, where he hopes to repeat his unprecedented
200-400 double of 1996. He has also said he will attempt to lower
the 400 world record, which he set with a 43.18 last year, to less
than 43 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's not the only reason for Johnson's limited
schedule. His wife, Kerry, is expecting a baby in early May. The
fewer meets on his schedule, the more time Johnson has with his
wife and child. TRACK IN `VOGUE' Track and field may be in vogue
because it's an Olympic year, but this month women's track and
field is really in ``Vogue''. High jumper Amy Acuff, pole vaulter
Stacy Dragila and sprinter Marion Jones are among a group of
Olympic hopefuls featured in the May issue of the fashion magazine.
Acuff, a professional model as well as a 1996 Olympian, is pictured
clearing a high jump bar in a Donna Karan aqua-mint silk chiffon
dress. She also appears in the April 17 issue of ``Us Weekly''.
</P>
<P>
   Dragila is just as hot in media circles. The 29-year-old former
heptathlete, who has broken the world indoor record and tied the
outdoor record in the past six months, is the star of a Visa
commercial in which she speaks dreamily of winning Olympic gold as
a diver before breaking the spell by revealing she's a pole vaulter
and admitting, ``I can't even swim.'' The women's pole vault will
be an Olympic event for the first time this year.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who is seeking a record five gold medals in Sydney, has
been more visible on the track than on television. She opened her
season last week with a stunning 49.59 in the 400 meters at the Mt.
SAC Relays in Walnut, Calif., easily the fastest time in the world
this year and the fourth-fastest ever by an American woman.
</P>
<P>
   Jones only ran the 400 because one of the five events in which
she hopes to compete at the Games is the 4x400 relay. She is also
chasing gold in the long jump and the 4x100 relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to send a message to the U.S. relay coaches that if
they need somebody to run a 400 leg, I'm ready,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Jones' husband, world champion shot putter C.J.
Hunter, won his event at Mt. SAC with a throw of 71-4. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Sprinter John Capel withdrew from the University of Florida
last week to concentrate on preparing for the Olympic trials. As a
freshman, Capel won the 1999 NCAA outdoor 200 title in 19.87,
faster than any American other than Johnson in the past 12 months,
and has run a 10.03 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former TCU star Bryan Howard posted the first sub-10-second
100 of his career with a slightly wind-aided 9.94 at Mt. SAC.
Howard finished a close second to Olympian Mike Marsh at 9.90.
</P>
</TEXT>
