<HEADLINE>
JOCKEY, TRAINER GRAB STAKES DOUBLE IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 STAR DERBY-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Victory celebrations usually are quenched
by champagne. But Ralph Ziadie shares the tastes of one of the
horses he trains, so the bubbly could wait after he won both the
$300,000 Lone Star Derby and the $300,000 Texas Mile on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Ziadie, what would you like (to drink),'' Lone Star media
relations director Darren Rogers asked after the victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottled water,'' Ziadie replied.
</P>
<P>
   Bottled water didn't work for Skip Away when he raced in the
Texas Mile in 1997. But bottled water is the only thing Sir Bear
drinks when he's away from his barn in Florida. It was the proper
fuel at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie as Sir Bear capped off the
biggest day in the professional life of Ziadie and jockey Eibar
Coa.
</P>
<P>
   Ziadie, a native of Jamaica who is based in Florida, first made
it to the winner's circle when Coa rode Tahkodha Hills past Jeblar
Sez Who by almost a length in the stretch of the Lone Star Derby.
About 45 minutes later, Coa had Sir Bear a nose in front of long
shot Lexington Park to win the Grade III Texas Mile in front of a
crowd of 16,119.
</P>
<P>
   First place for both races pays $165,000 to the owners of each
horse. Both Ziadie and Coa get about a 10 percent cut of that, more
than $30,000 each. Ziadie's in line for a bonus of $250,000 if
Tahkodha Hills wins any of the Triple Crown races. It's part of the
$1 million bonus that Lone Star has underwritten (the winning owner
gets $750,000, and the jockey receives a payment from the owner).
</P>
<P>
   Ziadie said he's definitely interested in trying to collect. He
won't race Tahkodha Hills in the Kentucky Derby in two weeks. He
said the Preakness on May 20 is a possibility, but he said it's
more likely he'd run in the Illinois Derby at Sportsman's Park near
Chicago on May 13. That would set him up for the Belmont Stakes on
June 10, and Ziadie and Tahkodha Hills' owner, Vernon Heath, think
that might be their best shot at the payday.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that amount of bonus potential, we'll surely go ahead to
one of the Triple Crown races,'' Heath said.
</P>
<P>
   He has a horse that suddenly has developed into a more versatile
runner instead of a one-dimensional closer. In his previous three
appearances in stakes races, Tahkodha Hills was never closer than
sixth at the midway point of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first half of the 11/16-mile Derby, Coa had Tahkodha
Hills laying third. Judging by the first week of racing at Lone
Star, a deep-closing style wouldn't work on this track.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' Coa said. ``And I knew today that there was no
speed, so I knew I had to be close. He had good position, and
everything worked out right.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds-on favorite Big Numbers was third.
</P>
<P>
   There was no need to change the way Sir Bear has been running.
He was the only millionaire in the field of the Mile, but there was
a question if the 7-year-old had seen his best days. He hadn't won
since the Met Mile at Belmont last May. But he had been in seven
consecutive Grade I or Grade II races.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Bear rallied from almost six lengths back after the opening
half-mile went in 454/5 seconds. Lexington Park held the lead until
Sir Bear got past with less than 100 yards to go, and favored Forty
One Carats finished sixth after fading from second. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
