 STAR-NOTES-TEX 
Big Numbers falters in Lone Star Derby (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Jockey Donnie Meche didn't have an
explanation as to why Big Numbers flattened out in the stretch and
finished third as the favorite Saturday in the Lone Star Derby. Big
Numbers came into the race after a strong second-place finish in
the Grade III Rebel Stakes at Oaklawn Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say about him,'' Meche said. ``He trained
real well. He just didn't run the race he did in the Rebel.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Numbers, sent into the race by Lone Star leading trainer
Steve Asmussen, was within striking distance of the lead entering
the stretch. He was no more than 11/2 lengths back of Jeblar Sez
Who and eventual winner Tahkodha Hills with less than one-eighth of
a mile to go in the 11/16-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   He held third, but he was beaten by almost three lengths. It
appeared the only adjustment Meche had to make came when he swung
the colt around Bullet Buzz in the first turn. But that got Big
Numbers off the rail, which has been dead most of the season at
Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bullet Buzz) got in front of me away from the gates,'' Meche
said. ``He went down on the fence, and I got to the outside of him.
He eased out and bumped me a little bit, but my horse was on the
bit the whole time.'' PARK STROLLS
</P>
<P>
   At odds of 96 to 1, Lexington Park was a surprise runner-up in
the Texas Mile. Sir Bear wasn't able to put him away until the
final 50 yards of the race. He made it tough on Sir Bear when he
bore out in deep stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got a little over-aggressive,'' jockey Jeremy Beasley
said. ``He's a competitor. He didn't do anything I didn't expect
from him.'' GRADED STATUS
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star officials are hoping that the Lone Star Derby can
attain graded status from the North American Graded Stakes
Committee. Though this is the first time a previous winner of a
graded stakes has won the Derby (Tahkodha Hills won the Grade III
What A Pleasure Stakes last year at Calder), Lone Star director of
racing Larry Craft said that won't help. ``It depends on how the
horses do after this race,'' Craft said. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Unshaded, an allowance winner at Gulfstream Park, came from
off the pace to win the $325,000 Coolmore Lexington Stakes on
Saturday at Keeneland Racecourse. Globalize was three lengths back
in second. Favored Commendable was fourth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mighty, winner of the Louisiana Derby, is out of the Kentucky
Derby because of an injury similar to carpal tunnel syndrome in
humans. Trainer Frank Brothers said Mighty could be out from two
weeks to two months.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lone Star handled its second-best wagering day all-time from
off-track sources with $4,033,587. Another $1.3 million was handled
on track, and the combined $5.3 million is third-best all-time at
Lone Star. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
