<HEADLINE>
DEAR COMANDANTE: SNITCH THREATENS OUR CONQUEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By O. RICARDO PIMENTEL  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX It's been one of the more common complaints. ``You
people are taking over.'' OK, you've got me. I admit it. There is a
conspiracy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dear Comandante: &QL; 
Re: The reconquest, status report.
</P>
<P>
   They're on to us.
</P>
<P>
   My apologies, Estimado Comandante. I know you told us that you
wanted this to be the stealth reconquest, but somewhere, somehow,
someone has ratted us out.
</P>
<P>
   I've been racking my brain for what went wrong. There has to be
a snitch. I believe our efforts to date have been flawless.
</P>
<P>
   We've infilitrated key industries. When the uprising begins, we
will be well-positioned.
</P>
<P>
   I know in the past you've criticized our choice of industries,
particularly fast-food restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   I repeat: Troops gotta eat, and they don't have all day to wait
for a table. Thank you for suggesting drive-thrus, by the way.
We're still working on widening them for the battle tanks.
</P>
<P>
   And, judging from your comments in your last dispatch, you must
have missed my memo about our gardeners. Those leaf blowers double
as flame throwers, well worth the added expense. Please help me get
this one through the Finance Department. Those eggheads are really
raising a ruckus.
</P>
<P>
   You expressed some doubts about the domestics we have placed
into the homes of the affluent. I repeat, they are spies, our eyes
and ears.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that last batch of ``intelligence'' was not particularly
useful. But, respectfully, the sarcasm in your last dispatch about
the value of knowing that Mrs. Jarrod uses generic brand detergent
was unnecessary. And, no, the fact that Susie Allred got $5 from
the tooth fairy is not particularly relevant.
</P>
<P>
   I remain hopeful, however, that this particular mission will
bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
   We are, per your instructions, still working on ``Silicon
Valley.'' We've had some success but mostly in getting in on the
ground floor. Well, OK, cleaning the floors, but the point is:
We're inside.
</P>
<P>
   I hesitate to bring this next item up, but the troops are
grumbling and I feel compelled to tell you what's on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   They get paid so little and are growing tired of being blamed
for everything from crime to halitosis. I know it's all part of our
bosses' grand plan to create a labor surplus to depress wages. But,
goshdarnit, these folks have families to feed, and they've got
feelings, too.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. They are not completely ungrateful. Your
plan to get the Border Patrol to concentrate efforts at the border
while leaving the number of jobs available untouched is really
paying dividends.
</P>
<P>
   We've noticed also the good works of the marketing department.
We just laughed and laughed when we first saw Dinky the Chihuahua
on that first commercial. We've noticed also how other commercials
are increasingly featuring our people with heavy accents. It's
almost like our old co-conspirator Bill Dana, aka Jose Jimenez, is
back.
</P>
<P>
   We fully subscribe to the acclimation process you are beginning,
getting people used to the accents they will soon hear all the
time. A stroke of genius, mi comandante.
</P>
<P>
   Please don't pay attention to some of the grousing you hear from
some of our people about the stereotyping. Those Mexican-Americans
are a pesky bunch, but will come through as our fifth columnists in
a pinch. After all, they went along with your brilliant plan to
celebrate Cinco de Mayo.
</P>
<P>
   And they've really jumped onto this bilingual education
bandwagon in a big way, though they have this bothersome worry
about making sure the kids are educated well.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, however, our secret is out. Someone is orchestrating a
counterattack on the reconquest, and we are being accused of all
manner of wrongdoing. They say we're on welfare, we bring drugs
and, I like this one, we just come here to ``squirt out babies.''
</P>
<P>
   I wish we had thought of these things, but we will continue to
avoid them, per your instructions, lest we attract attention.
</P>
<P>
   I will continue my search for the snitch on my end, but would
not at all be surprised if the leak is coming from you guys.
</P>
<P>
   Just hear me out on this one.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of background check did we do on Dinky? That accent
isn't entirely believable.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I've got to get back to writing on public-policy issues.
Say hi to the missus.
</P>
<P>
   Your faithful servant, &QR; 
O. Ricardo Pimentel &QR; 
P.S. Kudos to marketing for making salsa the country's No. 1
condiment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
