<HEADLINE>
GALAXY SHUTS DOWN COLD FUSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ With the best collection of firepower Major
League Soccer has to offer, the end result is still a big dud for
the Miami Fusion.
</P>
<P>
   With Eric Wynalda, the U.S. national team's all-time leading
scorer, and Roy Lassiter, the league's all-time leading scorer,
Miami was shut out for the fourth consecutive game, losing 2-0 to
the Galaxy on Saturday in front of 16,885 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Miami coach Ivo Wortmann, hoping to wake up his listless
strikers, benched Wynalda and Henry Gutierrez, but the results were
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda, from Westlake Village, finally entered along with
Gutierrez in the 64th minute, but the damage was done, allowing the
Galaxy to win their second straight match to stay unbeaten at
4-0-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Miami is) a team right now that is a little bit frustrated,''
said Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid. ``Once you can get up a couple of
goals on them, they're not necessarily all working well with each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy remained a point behind Kansas City (5-0-1) in the
Western Division standings after the Wizards beat Tampa Bay 1-0
earlier in the night to remain the only other unbeaten team.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Galaxy's good start, Schmid said there is plenty of
room to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a coach, so I'm always not completely happy,'' said
Schmid. ``You always want to see a little bit better, a little bit
more. We are still giving the ball away when we don't need to. But
the last couple of days of practice we knocked the ball around well
and tonight we knocked it around well at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami midfielder Martin Machon discussed his team's 405 minute
scoreless drought despite having such talented strikers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our patience is running wild right now,'' said Machon, a
former Galaxy midfielder. ``Our coach has to do something, that's
his job. He has to work doing the week to see what's wrong and do
better for the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusion goalkeeper Garth Lagerwey, starting his first game of the
season, was given a rude introduction moments into the match thanks
to a beautiful acting job by the Galaxy's Clint Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   On a Greg Vanney corner kick, Mathis was backpedaling as
Vanney's corner was knocked to the top of the penalty area. Fusion
defender Jay Heaps tried to slow Mathis by tugging his shirt, but
Mathis made it look much worse by falling hard to the turf,
catching the attention of referee Tim Weyland, who ordered a
penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   Vanney converted the penalty, giving the Galaxy a 1-0 lead in
the third minute.
</P>
<P>
   In the 55th minute, Galaxy midfielder Danny Pena finished off
the Fusion for good, converting an errant clear by Miami and
sending a return shot to the far post to extend L.A.'s lead to
2-0. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
